<h3>Hypertension</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Diagnosis at ≥130/80 mm Hg (ACC/AHA); most patients' goal is &lt;130/80.</li>
  <li>First-line agents: thiazide-type diuretics, ACE inhibitors, ARBs, dihydropyridine CCBs. Black patients without HF/CKD: prefer thiazide or CCB initially.</li>
  <li>Never combine an ACE inhibitor with an ARB. Check SCr/K⁺ within 2–4 weeks of starting or titrating ACEI/ARB; up to a 30% SCr rise is acceptable.</li>
  <li>CKD with albuminuria: ACEI or ARB first-line regardless of race.</li>
  <li>Pregnancy: labetalol, nifedipine ER, methyldopa are preferred; ACEI/ARB and direct renin inhibitors are contraindicated.</li>
  <li>Chlorthalidone is longer-acting and more potent than hydrochlorothiazide; watch for hyponatremia, hypokalemia, hyperuricemia (avoid in gout flares), and hyperglycemia.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Heart failure with reduced ejection fraction (HFrEF)</h3>
<div class="keybox"><b>Four pillars of GDMT:</b> (1) ARNI (sacubitril/valsartan) or ACEI/ARB, (2) evidence-based beta-blocker, (3) mineralocorticoid receptor antagonist, (4) SGLT2 inhibitor. All four reduce mortality.</div>
<ul>
  <li>Only three beta-blockers have mortality evidence: carvedilol, metoprolol <i>succinate</i>, bisoprolol.</li>
  <li>Sacubitril/valsartan: allow a 36-hour washout after stopping an ACE inhibitor (angioedema risk); contraindicated with a history of angioedema.</li>
  <li>Spironolactone/eplerenone: avoid if K⁺ &gt;5.0 mEq/L or eGFR &lt;30 mL/min/1.73 m²; spironolactone causes gynecomastia (eplerenone does not).</li>
  <li>Loop diuretics relieve congestion but do not reduce mortality. Oral bioavailability: torsemide and bumetanide ≈ reliable; furosemide variable (~50%). Furosemide 40 mg PO ≈ torsemide 20 mg ≈ bumetanide 1 mg.</li>
  <li>Hydralazine/isosorbide dinitrate: adds mortality benefit in self-identified Black patients on optimal GDMT, or substitutes when ACEI/ARB/ARNI is not tolerated.</li>
  <li>Avoid in HFrEF: non-DHP CCBs (verapamil/diltiazem), NSAIDs, thiazolidinediones, most class I antiarrhythmics.</li>
  <li>Digoxin reduces hospitalizations only; target trough 0.5–0.9 ng/mL in HF. Toxicity: GI upset, visual changes, arrhythmias — worsened by hypokalemia. Antidote: digoxin immune Fab.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Acute coronary syndromes</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Immediate: aspirin 162–325 mg chewed, plus P2Y12 inhibitor and anticoagulation per strategy.</li>
  <li>P2Y12 pearls: ticagrelor (reversible; dyspnea; avoid with aspirin maintenance &gt;100 mg/day), prasugrel (contraindicated with prior stroke/TIA; caution age ≥75 or &lt;60 kg), clopidogrel (prodrug — CYP2C19 poor metabolizers get reduced effect; avoid strong 2C19 inhibitors).</li>
  <li>Post-MI regimen: aspirin indefinitely + P2Y12 inhibitor (typically 12 months), high-intensity statin, beta-blocker, ACEI/ARB (especially if EF ≤40%, HTN, DM, or CKD).</li>
  <li>Nitrates contraindicated within 24 h of sildenafil/vardenafil (48 h for tadalafil) and in right ventricular infarction.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Atrial fibrillation</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Anticoagulate based on CHA₂DS₂-VASc (Congestive HF, HTN, Age ≥75 ×2, Diabetes, Stroke/TIA ×2, Vascular disease, Age 65–74, Sex female): generally recommended at score ≥2 (men) or ≥3 (women).</li>
  <li>DOACs preferred over warfarin except with mechanical valves or moderate–severe mitral stenosis (warfarin required there).</li>
  <li>Rate control: beta-blocker or non-DHP CCB (avoid non-DHP CCBs in HFrEF). Target resting HR &lt;100–110 bpm in asymptomatic patients.</li>
  <li>Amiodarone: monitor thyroid (hypo- and hyper-), pulmonary fibrosis, hepatotoxicity, corneal deposits, photosensitivity/blue-gray skin. Major interactions: roughly halve warfarin and digoxin doses.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Dyslipidemia</h3>
<ul>
  <li>High-intensity statins (≥50% LDL reduction): atorvastatin 40–80 mg, rosuvastatin 20–40 mg. Clinical ASCVD and LDL ≥190 mg/dL both warrant high intensity.</li>
  <li>Diabetes age 40–75: at least moderate-intensity statin.</li>
  <li>Statin interactions: simvastatin/lovastatin are CYP3A4-dependent (avoid with strong 3A4 inhibitors); rosuvastatin and pravastatin have the fewest CYP interactions.</li>
  <li>Muscle symptoms: check CK only if significant; rechallenge with a different statin or lower/alternate-day dosing. Ezetimibe, then PCSK9 inhibitors or bempedoic acid, are add-ons for very-high-risk patients above threshold.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Anticoagulation pearls</h3>
<div class="table-wrap"><table>
  <tr><th>Agent</th><th>Key points</th><th>Reversal</th></tr>
  <tr><td>Warfarin</td><td>Target INR 2–3 (2.5–3.5 mechanical mitral valve); CYP2C9/VKORC1 variants alter dose; interactions: amiodarone, metronidazole, TMP/SMX ↑INR; rifampin, carbamazepine ↓INR; hold + vitamin K per INR/bleeding</td><td>Vitamin K + 4-factor PCC (major bleeding)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Apixaban</td><td>5 mg BID; reduce to 2.5 mg BID with 2 of 3: age ≥80, weight ≤60 kg, SCr ≥1.5 mg/dL</td><td>Andexanet alfa (or PCC)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Rivaroxaban</td><td>20 mg daily with food (AF); avoid CrCl &lt;15; 15 mg with CrCl 15–50 (AF)</td><td>Andexanet alfa (or PCC)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Dabigatran</td><td>Dyspepsia; keep in original container; avoid CrCl &lt;30 (AF, with P-gp inhibitor considerations)</td><td>Idarucizumab</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Heparin/LMWH</td><td>HIT: platelets fall ≥50% typically days 5–10 → stop all heparin, start argatroban or bivalirudin (or fondaparinux per protocol)</td><td>Protamine (full for UFH, partial for LMWH)</td></tr>
</table></div>

